        <h2>What is NTP (Network Time Protocol)?</h2>
        <p>
            NTP is the <strong>internet standard protocol for synchronizing time between computer systems</strong>.
            It fetches time from highly accurate 'time servers' around the world to adjust your computer's clock.
        </p>

        <div class="blog-highlight">
            <h3>🔍 NTP Features</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>OS-level sync:</strong> Adjusts system time at the OS level (Windows, Mac).</li>
                <li><strong>Hierarchical structure:</strong> Stratum 0 (atomic clock) → Stratum 1 (primary) → Stratum 2
                    (secondary)</li>
                <li><strong>High accuracy:</strong> Can achieve ±1ms accuracy in ideal network conditions</li>
                <li><strong>Long-term stability:</strong> Prevents clock drift over time</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>How NTP Works</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Client (your computer) sends time request to NTP server</li>
            <li>Records request send time (T1) and server receive time (T2)</li>
            <li>Records server response time (T3) and client receive time (T4)</li>
            <li>Calculates round-trip delay and time difference</li>
            <li>Adjusts local clock by calculated offset</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="code-example" style="background-color: #f5f5f5; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 4px; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <h4>NTP Time Adjustment Formula</h4>
            <pre style="overflow-x: auto;">
Offset = ((T2 - T1) + (T3 - T4)) / 2
Delay = (T4 - T1) - (T3 - T2)

Example:
T1 = 12:00:00.000 (request sent)
T2 = 12:00:00.050 (server received)
T3 = 12:00:00.051 (server responded)
T4 = 12:00:00.102 (response received)

Offset = ((50ms) + (-51ms)) / 2 = -0.5ms
→ My clock is 0.5ms fast, so slow it down by 0.5ms
            </pre>
        </div>

        <h2>What is HTTP Date Header?</h2>
        <p>
            The server hosting the website we visit (e.g., Ticketmaster server) has its own internal clock.
            When a web browser sends a request, the server responds with a <code>Date</code> header indicating its
            current time.
        </p>

        <div class="example-box"
            style="background-color: #f9fbe7; padding: 1rem; border-left: 4px solid #cddc39; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <h4 style="margin-top: 0;">Example: HTTP Response Header</h4>
            <pre style="overflow-x: auto; background-color: #fff; padding: 0.5rem; border-radius: 4px;">
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 2026 04:25:15 GMT
Server: nginx/1.18.0
Content-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8
...
            </pre>
            <p>
                In the above example, <code>Date: Fri, 10 Jan 2026 04:25:15 GMT</code> is
                <strong>the current time reported by the server</strong>.
            </p>
        </div>

        <h3>HTTP Date Features</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Server independence:</strong> Each web server has its own clock</li>
            <li><strong>Standardized:</strong> Standard format defined in RFC 7231 (GMT-based)</li>
            <li><strong>Real-time:</strong> Receive current time with every request</li>
            <li><strong>Variable:</strong> Server admin can arbitrarily adjust time (rare but possible)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Why do they differ? 🤔</h2>
        <p>
            Even if your computer is perfectly synced to standard time via NTP,
            <strong>the target server's clock might be wrong.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>Main Causes of Server Time Drift</h3>
        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <thead>
                <tr style="background-color: #f5f5f5;">
                    <th style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Cause</th>
                    <th style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Description</th>
                    <th style="padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Impact</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
